    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Turbulence model selection justified for rotating machinery hemolysis application; hemolysis constitutive model selected based on published benchmarking for centrifugal pump geometries.",
      "rationale": "SST k-omega turbulence model selected based on published FDA pump CFD round-robin results showing best NIH prediction accuracy among RANS models. Giersiepen-Wurzinger hemolysis model selected over Heuser-Opitz based on lower NIH MAE in validation study. Model form uncertainty estimated at 6% and included in MC UQ distribution."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All model input parameters documented with sources and uncertainty ranges; uncertain inputs propagated through MC UQ; 95th-percentile NIH below clinical threshold.",
      "rationale": "Twelve model inputs identified and documented: inlet velocity (±1.5%), rotational speed (±0.3%), dynamic viscosity (±3%), RBC fragility exponent (±8%), RBC fragility coefficient (±12%), hematocrit (±1%), wall roughness (±15%), and five geometric tolerances (±0.1 mm each). Distributions assigned based on measurement data or published literature. All propagated through 1000-sample Monte Carlo. 95th-percentile NIH 0.0031 g/100 mL, below clinical threshold of 0.01 g/100 mL. A screening sensitivity study was conducted informally during UQ scoping to rank candidate inputs; the three highest-ranked parameters (RBC fragility coefficient, viscosity, inlet velocity) were assigned wider distributions. This screening was not formally documented as a structured sensitivity analysis and no hasSensitivityAnalysis record is registered in this package.",
      "uqNarrative": "Monte Carlo UQ performed with 1000 Latin hypercube samples. Convergence of 95th-percentile NIH confirmed at N=800 samples (change <0.2%). During UQ scoping, an informal one-at-a-time screening was used to prioritize which of 18 candidate inputs warranted inclusion; 12 inputs were retained. The screening results were used to set distribution widths but were not archived as a formal sensitivity analysis output. The dominant drivers of NIH variance are believed to be the RBC fragility parameters and inlet velocity, consistent with the screening exercise, but no Sobol indices or formal rank-correlation coefficients are reported in this package."
    },
